  abstract = {We present a compact Baker-Campbell-Hausdorff-Dynkin formula for the composition of Lorentz transformations \$e\textasciicircum\{\textbackslash sigma\_i\}\$ in the spin representation (a.k.a. Lorentz rotors) in terms of their generators \$\textbackslash sigma\_i\$: \$\$ \textbackslash ln(e\textasciicircum\{\textbackslash sigma\_1\}e\textasciicircum\{\textbackslash sigma\_2\}) = \textbackslash tanh\textasciicircum\{-1\}\textbackslash left(\textbackslash frac\{ \textbackslash tanh \textbackslash sigma\_1 + \textbackslash tanh \textbackslash sigma\_2 + \textbackslash frac12[\textbackslash tanh \textbackslash sigma\_1, \textbackslash tanh \textbackslash sigma\_2] \}\{ 1 + \textbackslash frac12\textbackslash\{\textbackslash tanh \textbackslash sigma\_1, \textbackslash tanh \textbackslash sigma\_2\textbackslash\} \}\textbackslash right) \$\$ This formula is general to geometric algebras (a.k.a. real Clifford algebras) of dimension \$\textbackslash leq 4\$, naturally generalising Rodrigues' formula for rotations in \$\textbackslash mathbb\{R\}\textasciicircum 3\$. In particular, it applies to Lorentz rotors within the framework of Hestenes' spacetime algebra, and provides an efficient method for composing Lorentz generators. Computer implementations are possible with a complex \$2\textbackslash times2\$ matrix representation realised by the Pauli spin matrices. The formula is applied to the composition of relativistic \$3\$-velocities yielding simple expressions for the resulting boost and the concomitant Wigner angle.},
